org.jcvi.jillion.core.datastore

Enum DataStoreProviderHint

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<DataStoreProviderHint>
      • org.jcvi.jillion.core.datastore.DataStoreProviderHint
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Comparable<DataStoreProviderHint>

    public enum DataStoreProviderHint
extends Enum<DataStoreProviderHint>
    DataStoreProviderHint describes implementation hints to help datastore factories return instances of datastore implementations for the desired scenario. NOTE: These hints are only guidelines; the factories might ignore any and all hints. It is also possible that the factory could return the same implementation for multiple hint values.
    Author:
    dkatzel

    • Enum Constant Detail

      • RANDOM_ACCESS_OPTIMIZE_SPEED

        public static final DataStoreProviderHint RANDOM_ACCESS_OPTIMIZE_SPEED
        Use a DataStore implementation that is optimized for speedily accessing records out of order using DataStore.get(String) or DataStore.contains(String) at the cost of possibly taking up more memory. For example, an implementation might use a Map as a backing store which will put all records in memory to allow for very fast lookups. This is a very useful implementation if all the data fits into memory and the client code that uses this implementation will repeatedly require random access to the data. Therefore, this kind of implementation should not be used for DataStores that contain many records or for DataStores whose records take up lots of memory.

      • RANDOM_ACCESS_OPTIMIZE_MEMORY

        public static final DataStoreProviderHint RANDOM_ACCESS_OPTIMIZE_MEMORY
        Use a DataStore implementation that requires randomly accessing records using DataStore.get(String) or DataStore.contains(String) but has been optimized to take up as little memory as possible. The implementation chosen will probably take more time to access records than RANDOM_ACCESS_OPTIMIZE_SPEED but the DataStore will take up less total memory.

        For example, if the input to this DataStore was some kind of file containing record data, then perhaps and implementation will only store file offsets to each record. This allows large files to provide random access without taking up much memory. The down side is lots of I/O must be performed to re-open up the file and seek to the correct file offset and re-parse the data each time a call to DataStore.get(String) or DataStore.contains(String) is called. Another limitation to such an implementation is the input of the data must exist and not get altered during the entire lifetime of this object.

      • ITERATION_ONLY

        public static final DataStoreProviderHint ITERATION_ONLY
        Choose this option if the only methods in the DataStore that will be called are DataStore.iterator() and/or DataStore.idIterator(). The DataStore implementation returned will be optimized for iterating over records using DataStore.iterator() and DataStore.idIterator() possibly at the expense of poor performance of randomly accessing records with DataStore.get(String) or DataStore.contains(String). Such an implementation is ideal for use cases where the contents of the datastore will only be iterated over in a single pass. For example, iterating over each record only once using DataStore.iterator() inorder to perform a processing task. This implementation choice is also an option for datastores that contain so many records that storing them in memory would cause out of memory errors or if the number of records exceeds Integer.MAX_VALUE.

        Since calls to DataStore.get(String) or DataStore.contains(String) may be so expensive, it is recommended that instances of that use this hint are wrapped by a cached datastore using DataStoreUtil.createNewCachedDataStore(Class, DataStore, int) if random access will be used.
